text:
Michael Morton was a young father when he was sentenced to life in prison for the murder of his wife — a crime he didn’t commit.

He missed his son’s childhood, lost nearly 25 years behind bars, and carried the weight of a system that failed him.

In 2011, DNA evidence finally proved his innocence.

He walked out alone into a world that had moved on without him.
user_description: Sharing truth, even when it's hard. Because there's just nothing better.

text:
She waited 63 years.

Clara Gantt never gave up hope that her husband, U.S. Army Sgt. 1st Class Joseph Gantt, would come home. He was captured during the Korean War and declared MIA but his remains weren't identified until 2013. In her 90s, Clara stood tall as his flag draped casket was finally returned.

She never remarried.

text:
Just finished reading The Guardians, a legal thriller by John Grisham—Highly recommend!

It follows the story of Quincy Miller, a young man who was sentenced to life in prison for the murder of a local attorney — a crime he didn’t commit.

He missed over two decades of his life, lost contact with the outside world, and carried the weight of a system that failed him.

In the end, a small legal nonprofit uncovered the evidence that proved his innocence. He walked out alone into a world that had moved on without him.

text:
After the Distant Shore by Eleanor Gray is a historical fiction novel that follows the story of a woman whose husband went missing during an overseas conflict and was declared MIA.

She never remarried. It wasn’t until her nineties that his remains were finally identified—bringing closure to a lifetime of waiting.
